ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `dh_installsystemduser` command is used to install systemd service files for user services in Debian packages. It performs the necessary actions to ensure that user services are properly enabled in the user's system after package installation.  If you have an application that needs to run as a user service under systemd, this command is very useful.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `--name=FILENAME` --> ðŸ“ Specifies the name of the .service file. If not specified, the name is derived from the package name.
    ðŸ”¹ `--no-enable` --> ðŸš« Prevents automatic enabling of the service during installation. You can manually enable the service using `systemctl --user enable`.
    ðŸ”¹ `--error-handler=COMMAND` --> ðŸš¨ Specifies a command to execute in case of an error. This is useful for logging or handling errors gracefully.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ dh_installsystemduser --name=my-awesome-app.service

    ðŸ”¹ This command installs the `my-awesome-app.service` file and enables the user service.

    $ dh_installsystemduser --no-enable

    ðŸ”¹ This command installs the .service file, but does not enable the service. The user must enable the service manually using `systemctl --user enable`.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

